How does one line of Spark code become work across a whole cluster? Follow it down.

It starts with the driver, which runs your code and hands the query to Catalyst, Spark's optimizer.

Catalyst refines it in steps: an unresolved plan becomes a logical plan, then an optimized plan, then a physical plan that's ready to run.

Tungsten takes over, generating tight bytecode and managing memory directly.

Now the DAG scheduler splits the job into stages. Stages run one after another, because each shuffle of data must finish before the next can begin.

Each stage becomes tasks, one per partition. The task scheduler hands them out, and unlike stages, tasks run in parallel.

Finally the cluster manager allocates executors, and those executors run the tasks across many machines at once.
